segments.text: So over the years, the Aggie players have developed a fairly sound financial basis.
I think so.
On their own.
I think so, yes.
They, I assume, own their own equipment.
Oh, yes.
You have lighting, sound equipment.
Oh, yeah, we've got quite a bit of lighting equipment.
But we're working quite closely now, or I presume this next year, and they're going to work very, very closely with us.
people over there in the center.
In fact, we've been working rather closely with them this last year.
We do some shows in the forum and we do, I did a show and two shows in the auditorium, the 750 seat auditorium.
My last show was over there, Play It Again Sam.
That's the last show that I directed here at A&M.
I want to tell you something about that, not that it's important or not, but the first play I did here back in 1950,
kind lady, a young fella here named Harry Gooding, who was then a student in the Department of Architecture.
And he played in that play.
And when I was getting ready to do Play It Again Sam, he called me and he wanted to know if, for sentimental reasons, he could play in this last show that I was going to do before I retire.
Well, the Aggie place right now is open only to students.
No faculty, no... Now, right now, he's working down there in the architect system building.
But I thought that was a nice gesture for him to ask to be in my last show.
And so he played in my last show and also in my first show.
He played Humphrey Bogart in the last show.
He played the role that Humphrey Bogart had played in Sand.
Well, that would be, I would think, quite an honor to you to have one of your former people come back, and particularly one from your first show that would want to have a role in your last show.
Well, Harry and I have known each other for a good many years, and we're pretty good friends.
He was with me for a long, long time, about ten years, I guess, before we turned it over into an all-students.
All-students.
Yeah.
Why was it decided to turn it into an all-student organization?
It would seem you would have had good success with student and outsiders.
Well, I'll tell you the reason for that.
Well, when we turned it into an all-student organization, at that time, women were not admitted to A&M.
But we had quite a bunch of people in there.
And personally, I don't think that faculty and students work together very well for any length of time in A&M.
in an organization like that, where you have to work so close.
I just don't think it works well.
Now, we've never had any men on the faculty.
We've had quite a few women, but they work quite well with the young lads.
You know, we've had awfully nice ones.
I want to say one thing right now, and I want to get this on the tape.
I've been running this thing for a good many years.
And we don't have any funny stuff going on in the Aggie players as an organization.
Not while they're around me.
They know the word is out.
Nobody comes around me while they've been drinking.
All they got to do is pass by me and they're out.
Now, I don't care whether anybody likes that or not.
But that's the first step in deterioration of a theater group.
You know, theater people don't have a very good reputation in this country.
They're looked upon as sort of theories and funny people.
But that's one thing.
And I have had, we've had a few little problems over the years, but they were settled and settled very, very quickly.
And I'll tell you something else.
I had one boy that I put out, and he came back within a year, and he said, may I come back in?
I said, yeah.
He got back in, and he eventually became president of the organization.
But he got erected.
Well, I would imagine particularly where you have an organization that's primarily student males and some faculty wives, you would have to run a pretty tight operation so as to not have problems.
I tried to run a tight organization.
And I think I was fairly successful with it.
Well, I don't think I have ever heard anything
other than good things about the Aggie players.
Well, I'm happy to hear that.
And I want to add one other thing here.
Over the years, I have never had anybody from the administration or anybody from the faculty claim that I chose and did a show that was not fit to be done.
I mean by that, a dirty show.
Never.
Now that's something.
And I'm very proud of that.
And many of the administrators have come to see our shows.
And you know what I mean by the administrators.
They've come to see our shows over the years.
And I have never had one call me on the phone, write a letter, or anything that they objected to the show.
I did have one time, many, many years ago, I did what was a command decision.
That was a war show.
And I did have one instructor come up to me the next day, and he said, my wife thinks that's a very awful show.
Well, there was a couple of dams and a couple of hells in it.
Well, these generals were in this little place, and these guys were flying over there dropping bombs.
Now, you know they weren't going to say tut-tut.
Yeah, yeah.
And I, you know, I didn't...
But I will not allow in any script of mine that I do any reference to a deity unless it's a lawful reference.
You understand?
Some of these funny little lines they throw in there.
I could go on, but it might mess up your microphone.
I won't go into detail.
But if I do not see that it adds anything to the script, I'm going to alter it or change it, and I don't think that's going to hurt the author because he's not going to know anything about it.
But a lot of these, and I won't say this word over this microphone, but a lot of these, you know, hitting your thumb.
I've taught my kids, you know, instead of an expletive, they can get a lot more bleeding out of the audience by silencing.
You understand what I'm talking about?
Huh?
Well, that's what I do with those kind of funny, stupid things they're having in.
Now, you notice, you watch TV a little, and you notice that they're getting a few hells and dams in there now.
Huh?
I don't think.
I'm not a Puritan, my friend.
I'm not a Puritan.
I know that happens all the time.
I do it myself.
But I don't see the need for that, really, when you come right down.
However, I will say they're very clever in placing these things today in their script.
Very clever about it.
But, well, I didn't want to get that annotated.
Now, what these kids do when they leave, I don't know.
I can't control that.
But when they're working for me, brother, I control that.
And I tell them there's three things that make, you know.
I want them to have some fun.
Fun and work.
You see?
Those are the two things that will produce a good show.
Idea, people, and space.
That's what theater is all about.
And that's the only three requisites you need.
Idea, people, space.
You can do a show in a cow fashion.
You don't need a building.
And that's what I've laid the premise, that's the premise of my theater work.
Well, I think that would be a premise for an awful lot of things.
Simplicity.
That's the thing.
Simplicity.
So frequently today, not only in theater, but in many other things, schools and everything, there's so much emphasis placed upon the facility.
Yes, yes.
We do too many things for these kiddos today.
Let them do these things themselves, make their own mistakes.
They learn that way.
When they build a flat, I'll give them the blueprint, let them go at it.
And when they get it all through, I'll look at it.
I'll say, you see that cornice down there?
Mm-hmm.
I'll say, well, look at your blueprint.
Oh, I got it on wrong, haven't I?
I'll say, yeah.
I'll say, now, make it again.
They cost me money, but it's worth it.
In the long run, they learn that way.
They learn.
and they'll stretch a canvas on a flat, and they'll glue-size it.
And I'll watch them.
They'll stretch it, you know, pretty tight, and they'll glue-size it, come back in three hours, and there'll be a big split up the middle.
I said, how'd that happen?
I said, did you read the instructions on the blueprint there?
No.
I said, well, you go back and read the instructions.
He really said, leave it limp a little before you glue-size it.
I said, now that'll...
Well, glue size is what you put on to fill the little holes in this cheesecloth stuff before you paint it, see?
Yeah.
That's the way.
That's the way.
Experience.
My kids learn theater by doing theater.
By doing it.
Among the Aggie players, then, each play you produce, you have the entire cast, the technical crew, and they build the set.
Absolutely.
They do all the work under our supervision.
You see, they take courses.
And incidentally, anybody that's taken a theater arts course must, at least this has been the way I've run it since I was...
ran director of the thing, they must participate in a current and live show some way or other.
They build a flat or, you know, work on a crew, one of the crews, lights, flats, painting, publicity, or acting or something, costuming.
So being in the Aggie Players is almost a requirement, in a sense, to being in the theater arts section.
No.
Anybody can join the Aggie Players, but they don't have to take theater arts.
What I mean is, if you are in theater arts, though, you must be in the Aggie Players.
That's right.
That's what I'm trying to get across.
Well, you must be in a show.
And how do you get in the Aggie Players?
You just walked in and say, I want to be an Aggie Player.
I say, all right, you're in.
That's all.
No dues, no anything.
And they can get out just as fast.
They can either quit themselves or be absolutely... You're talking about being in the Aggie players, and I think you mentioned something about you have officers...
No more.
We stopped being one of those things a long, long time ago because we spent so much time doing it.
We go from one show to another.
So you don't have any officers or anything?
No, we don't have meetings anymore.
You did?
Once we did, once we did, yeah.
And then did the organization then have something to say in what place you put on and that sort of thing?
Well, to be honest about it, no.
I've chosen a play.
I figured I knew more about what a good play was than a 19-year-old kid.
Let's be honest about it.
I've never had them complain about a show.
If they didn't like the play that I chose, they didn't have to show up for casting.
No, I...
Well, I mean, after all.
Well, there's a great deal to be said for experience.
Yeah.
However, I've listened.
I listen to these kiddos.
I figure that any good teacher, if he can't learn from his students, is not a good teacher.
I don't care if he's 16 years old.
True.
Listen, I think one of our problems today, we don't listen to these kids.
Every once in a while, they come up with a good idea.
And if they do, my golly, let's use it.
There's a gap right there, as far as I'm concerned.
They go, wow, that kid doesn't know anything.
He hasn't lived long enough.
Well, he may have something on the ball.
And if he does, heck, let's listen to him anyway.
We've been talking a great deal about the Aggie players.
We talked about some of the other things, primarily creative dramatics and premier players.
What led you to start those two programs?
I don't know.
I generally have an answer, if anybody can ask me.
I just can't put my finger on it.
Well, the premier players, I noticed that there's a bunch of them.
Several years ago, these high school kids didn't have too much to do.
They didn't want to work.
You know, today, when we have a hard time getting kids, they've got to go out and get a job.
But here they were, horsing around, fooling around, and I thought, well, let's work up a theater group for them, give them something to do.
We work them every day.
Mm-hmm.
And they do the same thing the Aggie players do.
They work on it every afternoon.
They're building flats.
They may be acting, building flats and painting this and doing that and playing with electricity and so forth.
We teach them a good deal of good theater work in there.
Well, you would have to if you do two plays in the summer.
Yeah, that's right.
And they're two full-length plays.
And they're not crummy plays either.
We do good plays.
No, do...
Do you have some kids work in both plays, or do you just split up the group?
No, we do one play the first month and then another play the next month.
We have two sessions.
Do some kids participate in both sessions?
Oh, yeah.
We have mostly repeaters.
They get in on the first one morning.
They sign up for the second.
In fact, this last summer we had more in the second half than the first half.
Do you have many repeaters from year to year?
Yes, you'd be surprised.
We do.
We have quite a few repeaters.
We had one kiddo came in, one kid I remember from downtown there.
He came in creative dramatics when he was about five years old and he went all through the creative dramatics and he went all through the premium players until he got into college.
Did he carry on with his theater work in the college?
He's a singer, really, what he is now.
He's studying music.
Pretty good boy, too.
Have you had many or any number of people who've been to Aggie Players who have gone on to professional dramatics or professional theater?
Wow.
Not many.
Not a few.
Do you remember Rick Torn?
No.
He's a pretty good actor out in Hollywood now.
In fact, I think he's over in Spain now, on account of the income tax or something.
But he was an Aggie player, and then he went down to the University of Texas, and he was quite successful in New York.
He was very successful in Hollywood.

and uh then there's some other people i don't know if we need to name them we've had several and there's several people i worked with at baylor when i was directing some shows up there for baker clue guliger for one i saw him last night in a movie blue he's been very successful in new york and he's very successful out there in hollywood he does a lot of tv work very good actor terribly good actor i've worked with him directed him and i've worked in shows with him too by the way
even at my advanced age then.
But it's been a great deal of comfort and a great deal of fun for me, and I'm going to miss it.
You said you did some shows at Baylor.
Was this, this would be during the summer while you were working on a master's degree?
They have up there, or did have, what they call summer stock.
It was the first collegiate summer stock company in this part of the country.
and you'd go up there and put out so much money and go to school and then you'd get so much back at the end of summer if and when and so forth.
But it was a lot of fun.
They had some pretty good people up there too.
You had a good faculty.
Can you tell us a little bit about your graduate work at Baylor?
Was that done entirely in the summers?
Uh-huh.
And your major work is what?
Your major field for the masters?
English.
English.
Yeah.
With a specialty in theater.
Oh, I have two master's degrees.
Yes.
Oh, I see what you mean.
Yes, yes.
I have a master's degree in English, English crit, and a master's degree in theater.
I did them in the summer.
So did you have to write two theses?
Mm-hmm.
What was your first?
The first thesis in English was the Francesca di Rimini motif in...
plays.
I traced it down in plays.
That's in the fifth canto of Dante's Alighieri's Inferno, the Paola and Francesca love story.
And I traced it, tried to trace it, to see how many plays had been written.
And strangely or late, I only found nine, and none of which were
Too good.
And this was done at Baylor?
Mm-hmm.
And what year did you receive that degree or do you remember?
I can't remember.
I can't remember.
I was an old man when I did that.
I think I was in, I don't know.
I can't remember.
But it was, so it was then it would have been?
59, wasn't it?
Or did I get the other one?
I can't remember, tell you that.
Well, anyway, after that master's in English, you went back and got a second master's in theater.
Yeah, yeah.
And what was your thesis in that field?
The theater work at Texas A&M College.
Oh, I can remember the date on that.
That was 1960, because that's as far up as it is.
The second master's was in 1960.
Yeah, it ended.
Yeah, yeah.
Okay.
Sound like 1949.
Was that right?
That would have been for the first one.
I don't know.
I think we probably can find that out if we need to.
Of course, in addition to being director of the Aggie Players, you've been the voice of Kyle Field for a goodly number of years.
I believe that also was 1950, was it not?
How did you happen to become that?
It's a strange story.
They were having a playoff game here on a high school level, Class AA, I can remember that.
And Ray Williams out of Austin phoned up here and he wanted some officials to do the ballgame.
And so they chose officials.
I went to the meeting and they said, let's broadcast it out of the stadium.
And they had then a little place about as wide as this desk, a little wooden shack down on that end of the

stands on the west side and west side yeah that's where the press box is it's on the south end of the west side and somebody there I don't remember who it was I remember the officials I met one of them yesterday and we had a little talk about that ball game 25 years ago and so I did that high school game
And I guess a few people heard me, and I forget who the coach was here now.
Was it either Ray George or Harry Steitler?
Steitler, I believe it's Steitler.
Harry, I believe.
And Bill Dayton was here at the time as a trainer, if I recall rightly.
And he came up to me in August sometime and asked me if I'd do the college game.
And I said, yes.
And that was all there was to it.
I mean, I've never had a contract with them or anything to that effect.
It was a request of the athletic department.
Yes, yeah, yeah, yeah.
That you did the voice of Kyle Fitts.
Yeah, the voice of Kyle Fitts.
You know, I kind of liked that.
Well, it gives you some contact with a different set of people.
Yeah.
Well, I coached football for quite a few years.
I refereed football for quite a few years.
I belonged to the SFOA.
And that's how I got into this athletic business.
I've been fiddling around in athletics either as a player or a coach.
spectator or announcer for about 50 years.
I've done everything in athletics.
You said you were a member of SFOA in the conversation chapter for a number of years.
At what level did you officiate games?
High school and junior college.
which must have been a pretty busy life for you during the football season.
Well, I gave up a lot of football games for the players, I'll tell you that.
I was going to say.
Oh, yeah.
Well, the players came first to me, and I, you know, pick up a buck or two here.
That wasn't so important to me as my organization, the players, which I felt and will feel until the 31st of August is mine.
Mm-hmm.
Well, I think you have every right to feel that way.
You know, it's a strange thing.
I used to, not too long ago, I'd go out around the country making little talks to groups of people, and invariably I'd be introduced as the voice of Kyle Field.
I used to get a little kick out of that.
But the thing is this.
For just a few hours a year,
I perform over there.
Nothing was ever said of the hours and the hours and the hours that I spent teaching theater and doing theater work.
You know how little things get stuck to you like that?
Isn't it funny?
That must be some kind of a...
on our society.
Well, yeah, I suppose, though, it's a few hours a year, but then...
I hit a lot of people.
You have a lot of thousands of people.
Yeah, I hit a lot of people.
At one point, at one time.
Over a single football season, you probably get as many people hear your voice as in several years of theater.
Well, of course, they don't hear your voice at all.
Only those people who are involved in the Aggie players, I guess, hear your voice.
That's right.
I venture to say probably that any number of those people who hear you at the football games are not even aware of the fact that you are director of the Aggie players.
They don't know who I am.
And it's well that they don't.
After all, the people come to see a football game.
They come to see the players play ball.
They don't come to hear me.
I just happen to be an adjunct to the ballgame, that's all.
But you will be continuing in that capacity?
I have been asked by the athletic department to continue as the voice of Kyle Field, and I told them I would be very happy, the good Lord willing.
How close of a contact with the athletic department have you had during your announcing?
I mean, obviously you have to know somewhat more about the players than the average spectator who comes.
Well, I go over there on rare occasions.
As a social visit.
And in the next few days, I'm going over and I'm going to get hold of the defensive coach and I'm going to have him show me their defensive lineups, the various defenses that they go into.
Then I'm going to get their offensive lineups, how they run the ball, and I'm going to know where these different players are.
And that's about it.
That's about it.
I don't bother them.
They don't bother me.
In other words, I don't go there and tell them how to run their football club.
They love that, I guess.
We have very friendly relationships, very friendly.
But as you say, people come to see the ballgame, not hear you.
That's right.
So your role as the announcer, Kyle Field, is considerably different than the...
television broadcast of the game.
Oh, yes, yes.
I work on this theory.
The less I say up there, the better.
And I've held that idea for 50 years, 25 years.
Why should I keep saying, well, now this quarterback is scratching himself.
He's under the ball.
They can see he's under the ball.
I don't have to tell them it's a first down and 15 yards to go.
They can see that on the scoreboard.
I don't have to tell them.
where the ball is on what line it is.
They can see that.
I used to have to when they didn't have a scoreboard.
You know, a fellow way down here, and he balled me on the five.
I said, the ball is now on the five.
He couldn't see down there.
He didn't know where it was, even in the field or not.
But they got all that stuff on the board.
I don't have to tell them that anymore.
But they can't tell who's carrying the ball half the time.
And they don't, you know, there's a lot of things they don't see.
They don't see a nice block.
There's one thing about this football that does bother me a little.
You know, the center of the offensive team does more work than any other one man on the ball club.
He has to do three things, four things.
He has to pass the ball to the quarterback when he's up there hand to hand.
He has to pass the ball for a place kick, and then he has to pass the ball for a punt.
Now, those are three entirely different things.
And on every single offensive play, he has to block somebody, at least one or two men.
Now, the other play, you know, you see this fellow prancing off here, just floating out there.
Nobody touches him or nothing.
He's a decoy, you know.
But that poor center, that son of a gun is right in the middle of
the hellhole of Calcutta, and he catches it every single play.
And he's got a blocker.
He does that for defense.
He'd get killed if he doesn't.
He catches it worse when he centers for the punt or the place kick because he's stirred upside down.
Yeah, that poof.
And you know, you can seldom mention a fella's name over the PA. You see?
Very real.
The only time he gets mentioned is if he snaps the ball over somebody's head.
No, I won't mention that.
No, no.
Yeah.
I don't say you, but in most... No, I wouldn't.
In the print, he would.
In most...
No, I think it was perfect.
No, I shouldn't say that.
In those broadcasts or televised...
I think they talk too much, to tell you the truth.
I really do think they talk too much.
Is this perhaps a carryover from radio when they were trying to describe the game?
No, I think it's a case of these fellows are so in love with their voice and they love to hear themselves so much they just got to keep talking.
I shouldn't say that, probably, but that's the way it appears to me.
And I don't know.
Because watching it on TV is different than being in a stadium.
